"&#xa0;\n6 December 2013\nINTRODUCTION&#xa0;\nWWF is a leading global conservation organisation, employing over 5,000 staff in more than 100 countries and with more than 5 million supporte\nrs across the world.  The UK charity\n - WWF-U\nK - was launched in 1961.  \nWe work in partnership with local communities, civil society organisations, governments, multinational agencies and the private sector on the issues of fresh water, biodiversity, climate change, forests, \nthe \nmarine\n environment\n, sustainable consumption, \ninfrastructure and energy\n.\n&#xa0;\nWe welcome the \nEnvironment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs \nCommittee\n’s Inquiry into food security\n.\n \n \nOur responses \nto the issues raised by the Committee \nfocus on those areas \nmost \nrelevant to our work.\n&#xa0;\nRESPONSES TO ISSUES RAISED BY THE COMMITTEEHow best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficientlyThe relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing itThe implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food securityThe potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food securityHow food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can contribute to increased resilienceWhether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new marketsWater security\nEcosystem degradation and biodiversity loss\nWays of increasing self-sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantageConclusion &#xa0;\nREFERENCES\n&#xa0;\n Th\nough this prediction has\n now \nbeen \ndowngraded \nto\n suggest \nthat \nwe might need to produce a maximum of 60% more food by 2050.\n FAO\n (2009) How to feed the world by 2050 - \nhttp://www.fao.org/fileadmin/templates/wsfs/docs/expert_paper/How_to_Feed_the_World_in_2050.pdf \n \n The Economist Confe